<script>

/**
 * jQuery Plugin: Sticky Tabs
 *
 * @author Aidan Lister <aidan@php.net>
 * adapted by Ruben Arslan to activate parent tabs too
 * http://www.aidanlister.com/2014/03/persisting-the-tab-state-in-bootstrap/
 */
(function($) {
  "use strict";
  $.fn.rmarkdownStickyTabs = function() {
    var context = this;
    // Show the tab corresponding with the hash in the URL, or the first tab
    var showStuffFromHash = function() {
      var hash = window.location.hash;
      var selector = hash ? 'a[href="' + hash + '"]' : 'li.active > a';
      var $selector = $(selector, context);
      if($selector.data('toggle') === "tab") {
        $selector.tab('show');
        // walk up the ancestors of this element, show any hidden tabs
        $selector.parents('.section.tabset').each(function(i, elm) {
          var link = $('a[href="#' + $(elm).attr('id') + '"]');
          if(link.data('toggle') === "tab") {
            link.tab("show");
          }
        });
      }
    };


    // Set the correct tab when the page loads
    showStuffFromHash(context);

    // Set the correct tab when a user uses their back/forward button
    $(window).on('hashchange', function() {
      showStuffFromHash(context);
    });

    // Change the URL when tabs are clicked
    $('a', context).on('click', function(e) {
      history.pushState(null, null, this.href);
      showStuffFromHash(context);
    });

    return this;
  };
}(jQuery));

window.buildTabsets = function(tocID) {

  // build a tabset from a section div with the .tabset class
  function buildTabset(tabset) {

    // check for fade and pills options
    var fade = tabset.hasClass("tabset-fade");
    var pills = tabset.hasClass("tabset-pills");
    var navClass = pills ? "nav-pills" : "nav-tabs";

    // determine the heading level of the tabset and tabs
    var match = tabset.attr('class').match(/level(\d) /);
    if (match === null)
      return;
    var tabsetLevel = Number(match[1]);
    var tabLevel = tabsetLevel + 1;

    // find all subheadings immediately below
    var tabs = tabset.find("div.section.level" + tabLevel);
    if (!tabs.length)
      return;

    // create tablist and tab-content elements
    var tabList = $('<ul class="nav ' + navClass + '" role="tablist"></ul>');
    $(tabs[0]).before(tabList);
    var tabContent = $('<div class="tab-content"></div>');
    $(tabs[0]).before(tabContent);

    // build the tabset
    var activeTab = 0;
    tabs.each(function(i) {

      // get the tab div
      var tab = $(tabs[i]);

      // get the id then sanitize it for use with bootstrap tabs
      var id = tab.attr('id');

      // see if this is marked as the active tab
      if (tab.hasClass('active'))
        activeTab = i;

      // remove any table of contents entries associated with
      // this ID (since we'll be removing the heading element)
      $("div#" + tocID + " li a[href='#" + id + "']").parent().remove();

      // sanitize the id for use with bootstrap tabs
      id = id.replace(/[.\/?&!#<>]/g, '').replace(/\s/g, '_');
      tab.attr('id', id);

      // get the heading element within it, grab it's text, then remove it
      var heading = tab.find('h' + tabLevel + ':first');
      var headingText = heading.html();
      heading.remove();

      // build and append the tab list item
      var a = $('<a role="tab" data-toggle="tab">' + headingText + '</a>');
      a.attr('href', '#' + id);
      a.attr('aria-controls', id);
      var li = $('<li role="presentation"></li>');
      li.append(a);
      tabList.append(li);

      // set it's attributes
      tab.attr('role', 'tabpanel');
      tab.addClass('tab-pane');
      tab.addClass('tabbed-pane');
      if (fade)
        tab.addClass('fade');

      // move it into the tab content div
      tab.detach().appendTo(tabContent);
    });

    // set active tab
    $(tabList.children('li')[activeTab]).addClass('active');
    var active = $(tabContent.children('div.section')[activeTab]);
    active.addClass('active');
    if (fade)
      active.addClass('in');

    if (tabset.hasClass("tabset-sticky"))
      tabset.rmarkdownStickyTabs();
  }

  // convert section divs with the .tabset class to tabsets
  var tabsets = $("div.section.tabset");
  tabsets.each(function(i) {
    buildTabset($(tabsets[i]));
  });
};

</script>
<script>// Hide empty <a> tag within highlighted CodeBlock for screen reader accessibility (see https://github.com/jgm/pandoc/issues/6352#issuecomment-626106786) -->
// v0.0.1
// Written by JooYoung Seo (jooyoung@psu.edu) and Atsushi Yasumoto on June 1st, 2020.

document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', function() {
  const codeList = document.getElementsByClassName("sourceCode");
  for (var i = 0; i < codeList.length; i++) {
    var linkList = codeList[i].getElementsByTagName('a');
    for (var j = 0; j < linkList.length; j++) {
      if (linkList[j].innerHTML === "") {
        linkList[j].setAttribute('aria-hidden', 'true');
      }
    }
  }
});
</script>

<h1 class="title toc-ignore">A primer on R</h1>
<h4 class="date">Last compiled on 17 September, 2020</h4>

</div>

<div id="what-is-r" class="section level2">
<h2>What is R?</h2>
<p>R is a statistical programming language. Its strength lies in the vast ecosystem of <strong>packages</strong> available for doing everything from basic statistics, to plotting, to biological data analysis. It is a great programming language to have in your arsenal.</p>
<p>A package in R contains functions that can readily used to perform a particular task. Packages exist in central repositories. Repositories are hubs where are packages are located. Two of the most popular repositories for R packages are:</p>
<ol style="list-style-type: decimal">
<li><a href="https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/available_packages_by_name.html">CRAN</a></li>
<li><a href="https://www.bioconductor.org/">Bioconductor</a></li>
</ol>
<p>CRAN hosts general purpose R packages, whereas Bioconductor is specifically tailored for hosting packages that cater to the bioinformatics analysis of biological datasets.</p>
<p>You will be using packages from both CRAN and Bioconductor for your analysis of RNA-seq data in the coming week.</p>
<div id="would-you-ever-use-r-in-future" class="section level3">
<h3>Would you ever use R in future?</h3>
<p>It really depends on the problem at hand. Some task can be done more easily in languages like Python/C, while for others, R is more suitable and will yield the quickest solution to your problem. If you want to be a bioinformatician in the future, or want to be involved in any kind of biological data analysis, getting to know these two languages is the bare minimum that you should do.</p>
</div>
</div>
<div id="installing-r-and-r-studio" class="section level2">
<h2>Installing R and R studio</h2>
<p>Please download and install these two software in this order:</p>
<ol style="list-style-type: decimal">
<li><a href="https://cloud.r-project.org/">R</a></li>
<li><a href="https://rstudio.com/products/rstudio/">R Studio (Open Source Edition)</a></li>
</ol>
<p>The first software is the R language itself that you are installing on the computer. On its own, the R software is cumbersome to use. That’s why you installed the second software (R Studio) on top of it. R studio is an IDE (Integrated Development Environment) for R. Working with R code using R Studio is much more intuitive and fun as it has all the tools you will ever need to develop your R scripts.</p>
</div>
<div id="r-studio-walk-through" class="section level2">
<h2>R Studio Walk through</h2>
<p>Please open R studio. You will observe that R studio has four main windows/partitions, as shown in the figure below:</p>
<div class="figure">
<img src="data:image/png;base64," alt />
<p class="caption">Different panes in RStudio</p>
</div>
<p><strong>1. Source</strong>: This is where new R files open up, and in these files you write all your R code. There are two important buttons in this window that you should know.</p>
<ol style="list-style-type: decimal">
<li>The <em>Run</em> button: This button only runs the current line (where your cursor is). Pressing it again and again will execute the code line by line. If you want to run multiple lines with one click of the Run button then you will have to select those lines first, and then press the Run button</li>
<li>The <em>Source</em> button: This button is used to execute all the code written in an R file in one go.</li>
</ol>
<p><span style="color: red;">Tasks</span></p>
<p>Open a new ‘R Script’ file (Go to File -&gt; New File -&gt; R Script) and write the following code in it:</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb1"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb1-1"><a href="#cb1-1"></a>a &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="dv">3</span></span>
<span id="cb1-2"><a href="#cb1-2"></a>a</span>
<span id="cb1-3"><a href="#cb1-3"></a></span>
<span id="cb1-4"><a href="#cb1-4"></a>b &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="dv">4</span></span>
<span id="cb1-5"><a href="#cb1-5"></a>b</span>
<span id="cb1-6"><a href="#cb1-6"></a></span>
<span id="cb1-7"><a href="#cb1-7"></a>c &lt;-<span class="st"> </span>a <span class="op">+</span><span class="st"> </span>b</span>
<span id="cb1-8"><a href="#cb1-8"></a>c</span></code></pre></div>
<ol style="list-style-type: lower-alpha">
<li>Save this file somewhere on your computer. Give the file some proper name (do not leave it as Untitled1.R).</li>
<li>Run each line of code line by line, and see the result in Console.</li>
<li>Select only the first two lines of the code, press Run, and see what happens.</li>
</ol>
<p><strong>2. Console/Terminal</strong>: This is where the results are displayed. This is also where you can <em>interactively</em> write code, and see the result immediately. The code written in the console, will not be saved. It is therefore better to write code in the source files in the source window, rather than on console.</p>
<p>So what is the console good for then? It has two functions: a. It displays the result of the computations that you ran, and b. You can write small bits of codes in the console to test the values of variable in your main R script. These small pieces of codes do not need to be part of your main script. You are just these small pieces of code to quickly test something in your main code in the R script files.</p>
<p><span style="color: red;">Tasks</span></p>
<ol style="list-style-type: lower-alpha">
<li>Write the code give below in the <strong>console</strong>, and see the result.</li>
</ol>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb2"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb2-1"><a href="#cb2-1"></a>c <span class="op">+</span><span class="st"> </span><span class="dv">2</span></span></code></pre></div>
<p>The variable c already exists. We just wanted to see what value we would get when we add 2 to the value of c. We do not want this line to be part of our main script. That’s why we wrote c+2 in the console to quickly test out this line of code. Scenarios like these where you just want to test a line of code, but not necessarily make it part of your main code, are perfect for console.</p>
<ol start="2" style="list-style-type: lower-alpha">
<li>Test in the following line of code in the console:</li>
</ol>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb3"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb3-1"><a href="#cb3-1"></a>c <span class="op">*</span><span class="st"> </span><span class="dv">2</span></span></code></pre></div>
<p><strong>3. Environment/History</strong>:</p>
<p><span style="color: red;">Tasks</span></p>
<ol style="list-style-type: lower-alpha">
<li>Observe the Environment pane. What is in it? What do you think the Environment pane is for?</li>
<li>Open the History pane. What is it for? Can you guess?</li>
</ol>
<p><strong>4. File/plots/packages/help</strong>:</p>
<p><span style="color: red;">Tasks</span></p>
<ol style="list-style-type: lower-alpha">
<li>What the Files pane for?</li>
<li>What do you think the Plots pane is for?</li>
<li>What do you see in the Packages pane.</li>
</ol>
</div>
<div id="the-basics-of-r" class="section level2">
<h2>The basics of R</h2>
<div id="operators" class="section level3">
<h3>Operators</h3>
<p>The basic operators in R are :</p>
<ol style="list-style-type: decimal">
<li>+(addition)</li>
<li>-(subtraction)</li>
<li>/(division)</li>
<li>*(multiplication)</li>
<li>^(exponentiation)</li>
<li>&lt;- (assignment)</li>
</ol>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb4"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb4-1"><a href="#cb4-1"></a>x &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="dv">3</span> <span class="co"># assign a value of 3 to a variable named x</span></span>
<span id="cb4-2"><a href="#cb4-2"></a>y &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="dv">12</span> <span class="co"># assign  a value of 12 to a variable named y</span></span></code></pre></div>
<p>In the code above, we have defined two variables, and assigned them values using the assignment operator <strong>&lt;-</strong>. The keyboard shortcut for placing this operator quickly is <strong>alt -</strong> (on MACs at least).</p>
<p>Variables are containers that hold some value. x and y above are both variables. Variables are called variables because the value they carry can <em>vary</em>. In the code below, we will change the value of variable y by one:</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb5"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb5-1"><a href="#cb5-1"></a>y &lt;-<span class="st"> </span>y <span class="op">+</span><span class="st"> </span><span class="dv">1</span></span>
<span id="cb5-2"><a href="#cb5-2"></a>y</span></code></pre></div>
<p>Variable names in R must begin with a letter. You can break up long names with a period, as in long.variable.number.3, an underscore (very_very_long_variable_name), or by using camel case (quiteLongVariableName); you cannot use blank spaces in variable names. R is case sensitive: Abc and abc are different variables. Good practice is to make variable names long enough to be evocative but short enough to type easily. For example, N.per.ha or pop.density are better than x and y (too generic) or available.nitrogen.per.hectare (too long).</p>
<p>The text starting with # is called a <em>comment</em>. It is commonly used to annotate the code with human readable text for better understanding. Anything can be written in a comment.</p>
<p><span style="color: red;">Task</span></p>
<p>Define a variable named first_name and assign it your own first name. Run the code. If it runs properly, then you have done it correctly. Otherwise, Google “Character Strings in R”</p>
</div>
</div>
<div id="help-in-r" class="section level2">
<h2>Help in R</h2>
<p>R has a help system. It is mostly used for reminding yourself about syntax or function details, and for giving cross-references, than for answering basic “how do I …?” questions. For questions such as “how do I…?”, it is better to do a Google search and then read the StackOverflow pages for solutions to your problem.</p>
<p>Coming back to help in R: If a function has a name, for example, <em>median</em>, then you can get the help using this command in the console:</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb6"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb6-1"><a href="#cb6-1"></a>?median</span></code></pre></div>
<p>This will open up documentation of the median function in the Help pan.</p>
<p><span style="color: red;">Task</span></p>
<p>Read the help of the function <strong>sd</strong> and from the documentation find if this function computes <a href="https://math.stackexchange.com/questions/15098/sample-standard-deviation-vs-population-standard-deviation">population standard deviation or sample standard deviation</a>.</p>
</div>
<div id="data-structures-in-r" class="section level2">
<h2>Data structures in R</h2>
<p>R has many data structures. These include:</p>
<ol style="list-style-type: decimal">
<li>atomic vector</li>
<li>list</li>
<li>matrix</li>
<li>data frame</li>
</ol>
<div id="atomic-vector" class="section level3">
<h3>1. Atomic Vector</h3>
<p>A vector is a collection of values of the same type. For example:</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb7"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb7-1"><a href="#cb7-1"></a>chr_vec &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">c</span>(<span class="st">&#39;John&#39;</span>, <span class="st">&#39;James&#39;</span>, <span class="st">&#39;Brown&#39;</span>, <span class="st">&#39;Harry&#39;</span>)</span>
<span id="cb7-2"><a href="#cb7-2"></a>chr_vec</span>
<span id="cb7-3"><a href="#cb7-3"></a></span>
<span id="cb7-4"><a href="#cb7-4"></a>num_vec &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">c</span>(<span class="dv">1</span>, <span class="dv">10</span>, <span class="dv">89</span>, <span class="dv">90</span>)</span>
<span id="cb7-5"><a href="#cb7-5"></a>num_vec</span></code></pre></div>
<p>The function c() is called the <strong>combine</strong> function. It combines multiple values into a single data structure.</p>
<p>It is important to note that a vector contains elements of the same datatype.</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb8"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb8-1"><a href="#cb8-1"></a>my_vec &lt;-<span class="st">  </span><span class="kw">c</span>(<span class="dv">1</span>, <span class="dv">8</span>, <span class="dv">3</span>, <span class="dv">4</span>, <span class="st">&#39;UiB&#39;</span>)</span>
<span id="cb8-2"><a href="#cb8-2"></a>my_vec</span></code></pre></div>
<p>In the example above, we tried to store 1, 8, 3, 4, and ‘UiB’ together. R first coerced the numbers into string, and then stored them in the vector. This is evident by the quotations &quot;&quot; around the numbers when you display the value of my_vec in the console. This goes to show you that a vector in R is a homogeneous data structure, i.e., all the values store in a vector should be of the same datatype (either all integers, or all strings, or all floats etc.).</p>
<p>You can extract a value from the character vector using indexing in this way:</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb9"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb9-1"><a href="#cb9-1"></a>second_item &lt;-<span class="st"> </span>my_vec[<span class="dv">2</span>]  <span class="co"># extract the second item from vector and assign it to a new variable</span></span>
<span id="cb9-2"><a href="#cb9-2"></a>second_item <span class="co"># displays the value of second_item in console</span></span></code></pre></div>
<p>The code below defines a vector containing values from 1 to 50:</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb10"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb10-1"><a href="#cb10-1"></a>num_range &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="dv">1</span><span class="op">:</span><span class="dv">50</span></span>
<span id="cb10-2"><a href="#cb10-2"></a>num_range</span></code></pre></div>
<p><span style="color: red;">Task</span></p>
<ol style="list-style-type: lower-alpha">
<li>Generate a vector of values from 50 to 100</li>
<li>Extract the first and last element from this vector and print their values in the console.</li>
</ol>
</div>
<div id="list" class="section level3">
<h3>2. List</h3>
<p>A list is similar to a vector but it can contain anything, including another list as well. This means that a list does not have to homogeneous; it can have a mix of different datatypes:</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb11"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb11-1"><a href="#cb11-1"></a>my_list =<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">list</span>(<span class="dv">1</span>, <span class="dv">2</span>, <span class="st">&#39;UiB&#39;</span>, <span class="kw">list</span>(<span class="st">&#39;a&#39;</span>, <span class="st">&#39;b&#39;</span>, <span class="st">&#39;c&#39;</span>))</span>
<span id="cb11-2"><a href="#cb11-2"></a>my_list</span></code></pre></div>
<p><span style="color: red;">Task</span></p>
<p>Observe the my_list variable in the Environment pane and visually compare it to the my_vec character vector to see the difference between these two variables.</p>
<p>Items in a list can be indexed using the notation shown below:</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb12"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb12-1"><a href="#cb12-1"></a>second_item &lt;-<span class="st"> </span>my_list[[<span class="dv">2</span>]] <span class="co">#extracts the second item from my_list and stores it in a variable name second_item</span></span>
<span id="cb12-2"><a href="#cb12-2"></a>second_item</span></code></pre></div>
<p><span style="color: red;">Task</span></p>
<p>Extract the second item in the inner list of my_list (in other words, get the item ‘b’) and store it in some new variable.</p>
<p>We can also define list such that each item of the list is named:</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb13"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb13-1"><a href="#cb13-1"></a>named_list &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">list</span>(<span class="dt">a =</span> <span class="dv">1</span>,</span>
<span id="cb13-2"><a href="#cb13-2"></a>                   <span class="dt">b =</span> <span class="dv">2</span>,</span>
<span id="cb13-3"><a href="#cb13-3"></a>                   <span class="dt">c =</span> <span class="st">&#39;UiB&#39;</span>,</span>
<span id="cb13-4"><a href="#cb13-4"></a>                   <span class="dt">d =</span> <span class="kw">list</span>(<span class="st">&#39;a&#39;</span>, <span class="st">&#39;b&#39;</span>, <span class="st">&#39;c&#39;</span>))</span></code></pre></div>
<p>Now, you can easily extract each of the item of the list by their names, like this:</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb14"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb14-1"><a href="#cb14-1"></a>named_list<span class="op">$</span>a</span>
<span id="cb14-2"><a href="#cb14-2"></a>named_list<span class="op">$</span>d</span></code></pre></div>
<p>The advantage of such names lists is that now you do not need to remember the index at which a particular item it. You just need to know its name, and using this name you can easily retrieve the corresponding value stored in the list.</p>
<p><span style="color: red;">Task</span></p>
<p>Define a named list with the following entities:</p>
<ul>
<li>read_id = <span class="citation">@rtuuk-2048fh4-ljkr-werjjt90</span></li>
<li>fastq = ATCGAGAAGGAGGAGA</li>
<li>quality = %^&amp;$&amp;%*%#%^()#@</li>
<li>length = 16</li>
<li>mapping_quality = 0</li>
</ul>
</div>
<div id="matrix" class="section level3">
<h3>Matrix</h3>
<p>R matrices are an extension of the numeric or character vectors. They are not a separate type of object but simply an atomic vector with dimensions: the number of rows and columns. As with atomic vectors, the elements of a matrix must be of the same data type.</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb15"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb15-1"><a href="#cb15-1"></a>my_mat1 &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">matrix</span>(<span class="dt">data =</span> <span class="kw">c</span>(<span class="dv">2</span>, <span class="dv">3</span>, <span class="dv">5</span>, <span class="dv">6</span>), <span class="dt">nrow =</span> <span class="dv">2</span>, <span class="dt">ncol =</span> <span class="dv">2</span>)</span></code></pre></div>
<p>The above code takes in a vector of 4 numbers and transforms it into a 2 by 2 matrix.</p>
<p><span style="color: red;">Tasks</span></p>
<ol style="list-style-type: lower-alpha">
<li>Open the help for matrix function. What is the default value of the byrow argument to the matrix function.</li>
<li>Set the value of byrow argument to TRUE like this:</li>
</ol>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb16"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb16-1"><a href="#cb16-1"></a>my_mat2 &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">matrix</span>(<span class="dt">data =</span> <span class="kw">c</span>(<span class="dv">2</span>, <span class="dv">3</span>, <span class="dv">5</span>, <span class="dv">6</span>), <span class="dt">nrow =</span> <span class="dv">2</span>, <span class="dt">ncol =</span> <span class="dv">2</span>, <span class="dt">byrow =</span> <span class="ot">TRUE</span>)</span></code></pre></div>
<p>What did the <code>byrow = TRUE</code> argument do? Find it out by comparing <code>my_mat1</code> and <code>my_mat2</code>.</p>
<ol start="3" style="list-style-type: lower-alpha">
<li><p>What is <code>TRUE</code> and <code>FALSE</code> in R.</p></li>
<li><p>Suppose you have a vector <code>c(&#39;a&#39;, &#39;b&#39;, &#39;c&#39;, &#39;d&#39;, &#39;e&#39;, &#39;f&#39;)</code>. From this vector generate a 2 by 3 and a 3 by 2 matrix. Both the matrices should be filled by row.</p></li>
</ol>
</div>
<div id="dataframe" class="section level3">
<h3>Dataframe</h3>
<p>A data frame is a very important data type in R. It’s pretty much the de facto data structure for most tabular data and what we use for statistics.</p>
<p>A data frame is a special type of list where every element of the list has same length (i.e. data frame is a “rectangular” list).</p>
<p>Some additional information on data frames:</p>
<ul>
<li>Usually created by read.csv() and read.table(), i.e. when importing the data into R.</li>
<li>Can also create a new data frame with data.frame() function.</li>
</ul>
<p>A dataframe is great for storing real world datasets where each of the dataset is a measured variable and each row is an observation.</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb17"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb17-1"><a href="#cb17-1"></a>dat &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">data.frame</span>(<span class="dt">id =</span> letters[<span class="dv">1</span><span class="op">:</span><span class="dv">10</span>], <span class="dt">x =</span> <span class="dv">1</span><span class="op">:</span><span class="dv">10</span>, <span class="dt">y =</span> <span class="dv">11</span><span class="op">:</span><span class="dv">20</span>)</span>
<span id="cb17-2"><a href="#cb17-2"></a>dat</span></code></pre></div>
<p>The above code makes a dataframe with 10 rows. Each row has an a letter and then two number x and y.</p>
<p><span style="color: red;">Task</span></p>
<ol style="list-style-type: lower-alpha">
<li>Make a dataframe containing the following four columns:</li>
</ol>
<ul>
<li>A character column containing <strong>first_names</strong> ‘John’, ‘Dimitri’, ‘Sara’, and ‘Bjron’</li>
<li>A numeric column containing <strong>test_scores</strong> of 10, 9, 6, and 8</li>
<li>A character column containing <strong>CGPA</strong> 3.9, 3.2, 1.2, and 3.7</li>
<li>A logical column <strong>has_passed</strong> containing TRUE, TRUE, FALSE, and TRUE</li>
</ul>
<ol start="2" style="list-style-type: lower-alpha">
<li><p>Locate the dataframe you just made in the Environment pane and just view the it.</p></li>
<li><p>Using the <code>dim</code> function, find the dimension of the <code>dat</code> dataframe. You can use <code>?dim</code> to read the documentation of dim function.</p></li>
</ol>
</div>
</div>
<div id="reading-csvtsv-files-in-r" class="section level2">
<h2>Reading CSV/TSV files in R</h2>
<p>Sooner or later you will need to read CSV or TSV file into R. You can do it easily in R.</p>
<p>In the data folder you have oil_production.csv file. First open this file in a text editor of your choice and answer the following questions.</p>
<p><span style="color: red;">Task</span></p>
<ol style="list-style-type: lower-alpha">
<li>At which line number the header of the dataset starts?</li>
<li>How many columns are there in this dataset?</li>
<li>By looking at the contents of the file, are the columns tab-separated or comma-separated?</li>
<li>Which columns of the dataset are numeric?</li>
</ol>
<p>Now lets read this CSV file into R.</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb18"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb18-1"><a href="#cb18-1"></a>df &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">read.table</span>(<span class="dt">file =</span> <span class="st">&#39;./data/oil_production.csv&#39;</span>, <span class="co"># Change this path as appropriate </span></span>
<span id="cb18-2"><a href="#cb18-2"></a>                 <span class="dt">header =</span> <span class="ot">TRUE</span>, </span>
<span id="cb18-3"><a href="#cb18-3"></a>                 <span class="dt">skip =</span> <span class="dv">4</span>, </span>
<span id="cb18-4"><a href="#cb18-4"></a>                 <span class="dt">sep =</span> <span class="st">&#39;,&#39;</span>)</span>
<span id="cb18-5"><a href="#cb18-5"></a><span class="kw">head</span>(df)</span>
<span id="cb18-6"><a href="#cb18-6"></a></span>
<span id="cb18-7"><a href="#cb18-7"></a><span class="kw">tail</span>(df)</span></code></pre></div>
<p><span style="color: red;">Task</span></p>
<ol style="list-style-type: lower-alpha">
<li>What happens if we set header=FALSE?</li>
<li>What does head and tail function do and how many rows do each of them print by default?</li>
<li>How would you display first 20 lines of the dataset using head() function?</li>
<li>Are there any missing values in the dataset? What is the representation of missing values in R?</li>
</ol>
</div>
<div id="functions-in-r" class="section level2">
<h2>Functions in R</h2>
<p>Functions are used in scenarios when we have a piece of code that needs to be used again and again <strong>at many different places</strong> in our R script. Rather than writing these lines of code again and again every time, we instead make a function of these lines, and we then just call the function (a function call is just one line of code) whenever we need to use that piece of code again. This strategy makes the overall code smaller, and also makes the code more manageable. Let see this with a silly example:</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb19"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb19-1"><a href="#cb19-1"></a>a =<span class="st"> </span><span class="dv">2</span></span>
<span id="cb19-2"><a href="#cb19-2"></a>c =<span class="st"> </span><span class="dv">3</span></span>
<span id="cb19-3"><a href="#cb19-3"></a></span>
<span id="cb19-4"><a href="#cb19-4"></a>sum1 =<span class="st"> </span>a  <span class="op">+</span><span class="st"> </span>c</span>
<span id="cb19-5"><a href="#cb19-5"></a>diff1 =<span class="st"> </span>a <span class="op">-</span><span class="st"> </span>c</span>
<span id="cb19-6"><a href="#cb19-6"></a>prod1 =<span class="st"> </span>a <span class="op">*</span><span class="st"> </span>c</span>
<span id="cb19-7"><a href="#cb19-7"></a></span>
<span id="cb19-8"><a href="#cb19-8"></a><span class="co"># some other code here</span></span>
<span id="cb19-9"><a href="#cb19-9"></a></span>
<span id="cb19-10"><a href="#cb19-10"></a>d =<span class="st"> </span><span class="dv">5</span></span>
<span id="cb19-11"><a href="#cb19-11"></a>e =<span class="st"> </span><span class="dv">6</span></span>
<span id="cb19-12"><a href="#cb19-12"></a>sum2 =<span class="st"> </span>d <span class="op">+</span><span class="st"> </span>e</span>
<span id="cb19-13"><a href="#cb19-13"></a>diff2 =<span class="st"> </span>d <span class="op">-</span><span class="st"> </span>e</span>
<span id="cb19-14"><a href="#cb19-14"></a>prod2 =<span class="st"> </span>d <span class="op">*</span><span class="st"> </span>e</span>
<span id="cb19-15"><a href="#cb19-15"></a></span>
<span id="cb19-16"><a href="#cb19-16"></a><span class="co"># some other code here</span></span>
<span id="cb19-17"><a href="#cb19-17"></a><span class="co"># some other code here</span></span>
<span id="cb19-18"><a href="#cb19-18"></a></span>
<span id="cb19-19"><a href="#cb19-19"></a>f =<span class="st"> </span><span class="dv">7</span></span>
<span id="cb19-20"><a href="#cb19-20"></a>g =<span class="st"> </span><span class="dv">8</span></span>
<span id="cb19-21"><a href="#cb19-21"></a>sum3 =<span class="st"> </span>f <span class="op">+</span><span class="st"> </span>g</span>
<span id="cb19-22"><a href="#cb19-22"></a>diff3 =<span class="st"> </span>f <span class="op">-</span><span class="st"> </span>g</span>
<span id="cb19-23"><a href="#cb19-23"></a>mul3 =<span class="st"> </span>f <span class="op">*</span><span class="st"> </span>g</span></code></pre></div>
<p>In the above code, we have 6 numbers in pairs of 2, and for each of these pairs, we are computing the sum, difference, and the product. As you can observe, there is a lot of repetition in the code. The repeated pieces of code happen at many different locations in our code, and there is other code (as shown by the comments) interspersed between the repeated code sections. This is the perfect scenario for using a function. We can make a generic function that takes two numbers as input, computes their sum, difference and product, and then returns the resulting three numbers.</p>
<p>Let us rewrite the above code again, but this time using a function they we will name as <code>sum_diff_prod</code>:</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb20"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb20-1"><a href="#cb20-1"></a><span class="co"># this is the function definition</span></span>
<span id="cb20-2"><a href="#cb20-2"></a>sum_diff_prod &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="cf">function</span> (num1, num2) {</span>
<span id="cb20-3"><a href="#cb20-3"></a>    sum =<span class="st"> </span>num1 <span class="op">+</span><span class="st"> </span>num2</span>
<span id="cb20-4"><a href="#cb20-4"></a>    diff =<span class="st"> </span>num1 <span class="op">-</span><span class="st"> </span>num2</span>
<span id="cb20-5"><a href="#cb20-5"></a>    prod =<span class="st"> </span>num1 <span class="op">*</span><span class="st"> </span>num2</span>
<span id="cb20-6"><a href="#cb20-6"></a>    output =<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">list</span>(<span class="dt">summation =</span> sum, <span class="dt">difference =</span> diff, <span class="dt">product =</span> prod)</span>
<span id="cb20-7"><a href="#cb20-7"></a>    <span class="kw">return</span>(output)</span>
<span id="cb20-8"><a href="#cb20-8"></a>} <span class="co"># function ends here </span></span>
<span id="cb20-9"><a href="#cb20-9"></a></span>
<span id="cb20-10"><a href="#cb20-10"></a>result1 &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">sum_diff_prod</span>(<span class="dv">2</span>, <span class="dv">3</span>)  <span class="co"># this is the function call</span></span>
<span id="cb20-11"><a href="#cb20-11"></a></span>
<span id="cb20-12"><a href="#cb20-12"></a><span class="co"># some other code here</span></span>
<span id="cb20-13"><a href="#cb20-13"></a></span>
<span id="cb20-14"><a href="#cb20-14"></a>result2 &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">sum_diff_prod</span>(<span class="dv">5</span>, <span class="dv">6</span>)  <span class="co"># this is the function call</span></span>
<span id="cb20-15"><a href="#cb20-15"></a></span>
<span id="cb20-16"><a href="#cb20-16"></a><span class="co"># some other code here</span></span>
<span id="cb20-17"><a href="#cb20-17"></a><span class="co"># some other code here</span></span>
<span id="cb20-18"><a href="#cb20-18"></a></span>
<span id="cb20-19"><a href="#cb20-19"></a>result3 &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">sum_diff_prod</span>(<span class="dv">7</span>, <span class="dv">8</span>)  <span class="co"># this is the function call</span></span></code></pre></div>
<p>As you can see from the above code, we have defined the <code>sum_diff_prod</code> once at the top, and then used it, or more precisely, called it, three times in the code underneath the function definition.</p>
<p>The function definition on the top defines inputs, outputs, and how the input are transformed into the output. Any two numbers can be provided to the function during the function call. The resulting three numbers are packed into a list, and then the list is returned. If needed, the resulting list can be unpacked like this:</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb21"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb21-1"><a href="#cb21-1"></a>sum1 =<span class="st"> </span>result1<span class="op">$</span>summation      <span class="co"># or sum1 = result1[[1]]</span></span>
<span id="cb21-2"><a href="#cb21-2"></a>diff1 =<span class="st"> </span>result1<span class="op">$</span>difference    <span class="co"># or diff1 = result1[[2]]</span></span>
<span id="cb21-3"><a href="#cb21-3"></a>prod1 =<span class="st"> </span>result1<span class="op">$</span>product       <span class="co"># or prod1 = result1[[3]]</span></span></code></pre></div>
<p><span style="color: red;">Task</span></p>
<ol style="list-style-type: lower-alpha">
<li>Write a function that takes in three numbers and return the sum of all three numbers.</li>
<li>Call this function three times, every time with three different numbers</li>
<li>Write a function that takes a numeric vector as input and computes sum, mean, median, and variance of all the number in the numeric vector.</li>
<li>Call this function two times, each time with a difference numeric vector.</li>
</ol>
</div>
<div id="loops-in-r" class="section level2">
<h2>Loops in R</h2>
<p>Loops are used to <strong>repeat</strong> a certain piece of code a certain number of times. Consider a dummy example: Let use say that we have two vectors a and b, each containing 5 numbers, and we want to add the contents of the two vectors element-by-element. Here is how you can do it naively, without using a loop:</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb22"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb22-1"><a href="#cb22-1"></a>a &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="dv">1</span><span class="op">:</span><span class="dv">5</span></span>
<span id="cb22-2"><a href="#cb22-2"></a>b &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="dv">100</span><span class="op">:</span><span class="dv">105</span></span>
<span id="cb22-3"><a href="#cb22-3"></a>c &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">vector</span>()</span>
<span id="cb22-4"><a href="#cb22-4"></a></span>
<span id="cb22-5"><a href="#cb22-5"></a>c[<span class="dv">1</span>] &lt;-<span class="st"> </span>a[<span class="dv">1</span>] <span class="op">+</span><span class="st"> </span>b[<span class="dv">1</span>]</span>
<span id="cb22-6"><a href="#cb22-6"></a>c[<span class="dv">2</span>] &lt;-<span class="st"> </span>a[<span class="dv">2</span>] <span class="op">+</span><span class="st"> </span>b[<span class="dv">2</span>]</span>
<span id="cb22-7"><a href="#cb22-7"></a>c[<span class="dv">3</span>] &lt;-<span class="st"> </span>a[<span class="dv">3</span>] <span class="op">+</span><span class="st"> </span>b[<span class="dv">3</span>]</span>
<span id="cb22-8"><a href="#cb22-8"></a>c[<span class="dv">4</span>] &lt;-<span class="st"> </span>a[<span class="dv">4</span>] <span class="op">+</span><span class="st"> </span>b[<span class="dv">4</span>]</span>
<span id="cb22-9"><a href="#cb22-9"></a>c[<span class="dv">5</span>] &lt;-<span class="st"> </span>a[<span class="dv">5</span>] <span class="op">+</span><span class="st"> </span>b[<span class="dv">5</span>]</span></code></pre></div>
<p>Notice the repetition in the last 5 lines of the above code. There is no other code interspersed between these last 5 lines of code. This is the perfect scenario for using a loop. Let us see how we can do the same thing using a <code>for</code> loop in R.</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb23"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb23-1"><a href="#cb23-1"></a>a &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="dv">1</span><span class="op">:</span><span class="dv">5</span></span>
<span id="cb23-2"><a href="#cb23-2"></a>b &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="dv">100</span><span class="op">:</span><span class="dv">105</span></span>
<span id="cb23-3"><a href="#cb23-3"></a>c &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">vector</span>()</span>
<span id="cb23-4"><a href="#cb23-4"></a><span class="cf">for</span> (i <span class="cf">in</span> <span class="kw">seq_along</span>(a)) {</span>
<span id="cb23-5"><a href="#cb23-5"></a>    c[i] &lt;-<span class="st"> </span>a[i] <span class="op">+</span><span class="st"> </span>b[i]</span>
<span id="cb23-6"><a href="#cb23-6"></a>}</span>
<span id="cb23-7"><a href="#cb23-7"></a></span>
<span id="cb23-8"><a href="#cb23-8"></a>c <span class="co"># displays the content of c in the console</span></span></code></pre></div>
<p>Now the code is much more compact.</p>
<p><span style="color: red;">Task</span></p>
<ol style="list-style-type: lower-alpha">
<li>What is the purpose of the seq_along() function. Read its help to find out.</li>
<li>What is the purpose of i in the above code?</li>
<li>When do you use a function and when do you use a loop?</li>
</ol>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb24"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb24-1"><a href="#cb24-1"></a>a &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="dv">100</span><span class="op">:</span><span class="dv">1000</span></span></code></pre></div>
<p>Write a for loop that prints out each element of the vector a defined above.</p>
</div>
<div id="installing-packages-in-r" class="section level2">
<h2>Installing packages in R</h2>
<p>As stated earlier, the availability of different packages is what makes R so great. At some point or the other you will need to install packages. CRAN and bioconductor packages are installed in different ways:</p>
<div id="installing-a-cran-package" class="section level3">
<h3>Installing a CRAN package</h3>
<p>Let us install two important packages (dplyr, ggplot2) from CRAN. Run the following code:</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb25"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb25-1"><a href="#cb25-1"></a><span class="kw">install.packages</span>(<span class="kw">c</span>(<span class="st">&quot;dplyr&quot;</span>, <span class="st">&quot;ggplot2&quot;</span>))</span></code></pre></div>
<p>Note that a package needs to be installed only once, so you only need to run this code once. Once these packages are installed, you will not need to run this code again. This is true for bioconductor packages as well.</p>
</div>
<div id="installing-a-bioconductor-package" class="section level3">
<h3>Installing a Bioconductor package</h3>
<p>Let us install two Bioconductor packages (DESeq2 and edgeRs)</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb26"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb26-1"><a href="#cb26-1"></a><span class="cf">if</span> (<span class="op">!</span><span class="kw">requireNamespace</span>(<span class="st">&quot;BiocManager&quot;</span>, <span class="dt">quietly =</span> <span class="ot">TRUE</span>))</span>
<span id="cb26-2"><a href="#cb26-2"></a>    <span class="kw">install.packages</span>(<span class="st">&quot;BiocManager&quot;</span>)</span>
<span id="cb26-3"><a href="#cb26-3"></a></span>
<span id="cb26-4"><a href="#cb26-4"></a>BiocManager<span class="op">::</span><span class="kw">install</span>(<span class="kw">c</span>(<span class="st">&quot;edgeR&quot;</span>, <span class="st">&quot;DESeq2&quot;</span>))</span></code></pre></div>
</div>
<div id="using-packages" class="section level3">
<h3>Using packages</h3>
<p>Just because you have installed an R or bioconductor package, doesn’t mean that you can use it. To be able to use a package, you must first load the package into your R script. Once the package is loaded then you can use the package functions.</p>
<p>For example to use the functions from ggplot2 and edgeR, you will need to load them first using the commands below:</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb27"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb27-1"><a href="#cb27-1"></a><span class="kw">library</span>(ggplot2)</span>
<span id="cb27-2"><a href="#cb27-2"></a><span class="kw">library</span>(edgeR)</span></code></pre></div>
</div>
</div>
<div id="basics-of-data-visulization-in-r" class="section level2">
<h2>Basics of data visulization in R</h2>
<p>Data visualization is an essential skill for any scientist as it can reveal important insights about the data that are not obvious from just viewing the numeric data. R shines when it comes to data visualization due to its famous package <strong>ggplot2</strong>. Most of the graphs that you see in newspapers and online articles are created using this package. Once you get a hang of it, creating a plot using ggplot2 is very easy and intuitive.</p>
<p>To learn ggplot2, please visit this <a href="https://uc-r.github.io/ggplot_intro">online tutorial</a>.</p>
<p>Do not fret if you are not able to go fully through the tutorial. No one can remember all this code. More often than not, you just Google for the kind of plot that you need, and out comes the code that you can use to get the plot. Over time, you start to remember the code, and then you no longer need to Google.</p>
<p>For now, just learn enough ggplot2 that you can create simple scatter, line plot, box plots, and histograms.</p>
<p><span style="color: red;">Task</span></p>
<ol style="list-style-type: lower-alpha">
<li>Using ggplot2 and the dataframe defined below, plot a simple line graph of x_var(on x-axis) vs. y_var (on y-axis)</li>
</ol>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb28"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb28-1"><a href="#cb28-1"></a><span class="kw">library</span>(ggplot2)</span>
<span id="cb28-2"><a href="#cb28-2"></a></span>
<span id="cb28-3"><a href="#cb28-3"></a><span class="co"># simulate example data</span></span>
<span id="cb28-4"><a href="#cb28-4"></a>x_var &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">runif</span>(<span class="dv">20</span>, <span class="dv">0</span>, <span class="dv">100</span>)</span>
<span id="cb28-5"><a href="#cb28-5"></a>y_var &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="dv">5</span><span class="op">*</span>x_var <span class="op">+</span><span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">rnorm</span>(<span class="dv">20</span>, <span class="dv">0</span>, <span class="dv">10</span>)</span>
<span id="cb28-6"><a href="#cb28-6"></a>df &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">data.frame</span>(x_var, y_var)</span></code></pre></div>
<ol start="2" style="list-style-type: lower-alpha">
<li>Using ggplot2 and the dataframe defined below, plot a scatter plot of x_var(on x-axis) vs. y_var (on y-axis)</li>
</ol>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb29"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb29-1"><a href="#cb29-1"></a><span class="kw">library</span>(ggplot2)</span>
<span id="cb29-2"><a href="#cb29-2"></a></span>
<span id="cb29-3"><a href="#cb29-3"></a><span class="co"># simulate example data</span></span>
<span id="cb29-4"><a href="#cb29-4"></a>x_var &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">rnorm</span>(<span class="dv">100</span>, <span class="dv">0</span>, <span class="dv">1</span>)</span>
<span id="cb29-5"><a href="#cb29-5"></a>y_var &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">rnorm</span>(<span class="dv">100</span>, <span class="dv">5</span>, <span class="dv">1</span>)</span>
<span id="cb29-6"><a href="#cb29-6"></a>df &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">data.frame</span>(x_var, y_var)</span></code></pre></div>
<ol start="3" style="list-style-type: lower-alpha">
<li>Using ggplot2 and the dataframe defined below, plot histograms of x_var, y_var columns of df. Are these two columns normally distributed?</li>
</ol>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb30"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb30-1"><a href="#cb30-1"></a><span class="kw">library</span>(ggplot2)</span>
<span id="cb30-2"><a href="#cb30-2"></a></span>
<span id="cb30-3"><a href="#cb30-3"></a><span class="co"># simulate example data</span></span>
<span id="cb30-4"><a href="#cb30-4"></a>x_var &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">rnorm</span>(<span class="dv">1000</span>, <span class="dv">0</span>, <span class="dv">1</span>)</span>
<span id="cb30-5"><a href="#cb30-5"></a>y_var &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">rnorm</span>(<span class="dv">1000</span>, <span class="dv">5</span>, <span class="dv">1</span>)</span>
<span id="cb30-6"><a href="#cb30-6"></a>df &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">data.frame</span>(x_var, y_var)</span></code></pre></div>
<p>Let us now plot a boxplot using ggplot2.</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb31"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb31-1"><a href="#cb31-1"></a><span class="kw">library</span>(ggplot2)</span>
<span id="cb31-2"><a href="#cb31-2"></a><span class="co"># simulate example data</span></span>
<span id="cb31-3"><a href="#cb31-3"></a>height &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">rnorm</span>(<span class="dv">1000</span>, <span class="dv">5</span>, <span class="dv">1</span>)</span>
<span id="cb31-4"><a href="#cb31-4"></a>weight &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">rnorm</span>(<span class="dv">1000</span>, <span class="dv">20</span>, <span class="dv">1</span>)</span>
<span id="cb31-5"><a href="#cb31-5"></a>df &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">data.frame</span>(height, weight)</span>
<span id="cb31-6"><a href="#cb31-6"></a><span class="kw">ggplot</span>(<span class="dt">data =</span> df, <span class="kw">aes</span>(<span class="dt">y =</span> height)) <span class="op">+</span><span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">geom_boxplot</span>() <span class="co"># for plotting the box plot of height</span></span>
<span id="cb31-7"><a href="#cb31-7"></a><span class="kw">ggplot</span>(<span class="dt">data =</span> df, <span class="kw">aes</span>(<span class="dt">y =</span> weight)) <span class="op">+</span><span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">geom_boxplot</span>() <span class="co"># for plotting the box plot of weight</span></span></code></pre></div>
<p>If you would like to plot the boxplots of both height and weight in a single plot, then you need to convert the dataframe from wide format (that it is currently in) to a long format using the function <code>stack</code>.</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb32"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb32-1"><a href="#cb32-1"></a>df_stacked &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">stack</span>(df)</span>
<span id="cb32-2"><a href="#cb32-2"></a><span class="kw">ggplot</span>(<span class="dt">data =</span> df_stacked, <span class="kw">aes</span>(<span class="dt">y =</span> values, <span class="dt">x =</span> ind)) <span class="op">+</span><span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">geom_boxplot</span>()</span></code></pre></div>
</div>
<div id="basic-of-data-wrangling-in-r" class="section level2">
<h2>Basic of data wrangling in R</h2>
<p>At some point you will have to deal with large datasets where you will to do all kinds of manipulations such as filtering the rows, creating new columns from existing columns, merging two datasets together etc. That’s where R’s <code>dplyr</code> package comes into the picture. This package makes data wrangling a breeze. You must know a few basics of this package.</p>
<p>Let us consider this code:</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb33"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb33-1"><a href="#cb33-1"></a><span class="kw">library</span>(dplyr)</span>
<span id="cb33-2"><a href="#cb33-2"></a></span>
<span id="cb33-3"><a href="#cb33-3"></a>df_<span class="dv">1</span> &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">data.frame</span>(<span class="dt">name =</span> <span class="kw">c</span>(<span class="st">&#39;Cinthia&#39;</span>, <span class="st">&#39;Joanna&#39;</span>, <span class="st">&#39;Jules&#39;</span>, <span class="st">&#39;Brookes&#39;</span>, <span class="st">&#39;Marry&#39;</span>, <span class="st">&#39;Stephan&#39;</span>),</span>
<span id="cb33-4"><a href="#cb33-4"></a>                   <span class="dt">inf100_score =</span> <span class="kw">c</span>(<span class="dv">100</span>, <span class="dv">90</span>, <span class="dv">80</span>, <span class="dv">95</span>, <span class="dv">25</span>, <span class="dv">40</span>))</span>
<span id="cb33-5"><a href="#cb33-5"></a></span>
<span id="cb33-6"><a href="#cb33-6"></a>df_<span class="dv">2</span> &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">data.frame</span>(<span class="dt">name =</span> <span class="kw">c</span>(<span class="st">&#39;Cinthia&#39;</span>, <span class="st">&#39;Joanna&#39;</span>, <span class="st">&#39;James&#39;</span>, <span class="st">&#39;Brookes&#39;</span>, <span class="st">&#39;Mathias&#39;</span>, <span class="st">&#39;Stephan&#39;</span>),</span>
<span id="cb33-7"><a href="#cb33-7"></a>                   <span class="dt">binf201_score =</span> <span class="kw">c</span>(<span class="dv">85</span>, <span class="dv">25</span>, <span class="dv">68</span>, <span class="dv">90</span>, <span class="dv">40</span>, <span class="dv">100</span>))</span></code></pre></div>
<p>Consider this dummy examples as a real world example, where we have two big dataframes of students and their scores on inf_100 and binf201. Both dataframes have some students common among them.</p>
<p>More often than not, you will need to merge information from two dataframes together based on some common column among the two dataframes. In the example above, we can merge the two data frames by the <code>name</code> column.</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb34"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb34-1"><a href="#cb34-1"></a>df_full &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">full_join</span>(df_<span class="dv">1</span>, df_<span class="dv">2</span>, <span class="dt">by=</span><span class="st">&#39;name)</span></span></code></pre></div>
<p>The above command will merge the two dataframe keeping all the rows of both dataframes. It uses NA for rows where the data is not available. Please view df_full in the Environment pane by clicking on it. What is the value of <code>binf201_score</code> for <code>Jules</code> in <code>df_full</code></p>
<p>What if we want to merge the two dataframes, but want only want students in the df_1 to be in the new dataframe. Here is how you can do it:</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb35"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb35-1"><a href="#cb35-1"></a>df_left &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">left_join</span>(df_<span class="dv">1</span>, df_<span class="dv">2</span>, <span class="dt">by=</span><span class="st">&#39;name)</span></span></code></pre></div>
<p>What if we want to merge the two dataframes, but want only want students in the df_2 to be in the new dataframe. Here is how you can do it:</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb36"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb36-1"><a href="#cb36-1"></a>df_right &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">right_join</span>(df_<span class="dv">1</span>, df_<span class="dv">2</span>, <span class="dt">by=</span><span class="st">&#39;name)</span></span></code></pre></div>
<p>What if we want to merge the two dataframes, but want only the students for which their an entry in both df_1 and df_2. Here is how you can do it:</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb37"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb37-1"><a href="#cb37-1"></a>df_inner &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">inner_join</span>(df_<span class="dv">1</span>, df_<span class="dv">2</span>, <span class="dt">by=</span><span class="st">&#39;name)</span></span></code></pre></div>
<p>left_join, right_join, full_join, inner_join all dplyr functions. There are many dplyr functions (such as select, filter, mutate, groupby etc.) for doing basic data manipulation tasks.</p>
<p>If you are interested to know more about, and if you have time, then please go through this <a href="http://sachaepskamp.com/files/dplyrTutorial.html">excellent tutorial about dplyr</a>. You do not need to know all this information in order to do coming week’s exercises, but as I said earlier, R is a very important language to know. If you have learned how to work with dplyr and ggplot2 then you can do pretty much any type of data analysis easily in R. These are basics that you should know, and these will make your life a lot easier.</p>
</div>
